excerpt: Displays on art & science, from paintings and prints to fossils & scientific instruments.
detail_description: Teylers Museum, the oldest museum in the Netherlands, offers a captivating journey through art and science. Its extensive collection features masterful paintings, drawings by renowned artists, ancient fossils, minerals, scientific instruments, and books. The museum also hosts intriguing exhibitions that highlight awe-inspiring science and art.
name: Teylers Museum

excerpt: Gallery in a 17th-century building dedicated to portrait painter Frans Hals & the Dutch Old Masters.
detail_description: The Frans Hals Museum, located in a 17th-century building in Haarlem, is a popular destination for art enthusiasts. It houses an extensive collection of artworks by the renowned portrait painter Frans Hals and other Dutch Old Masters. The museum also features modern art and boasts a charming inner courtyard with hedge mazes, flower arrangements, and seating areas. Visitors can immerse themselves in the life and career of Frans Hals while admiring his magnificent paintings.
name: Frans Hals Museum

detail_description: Jopen, a renowned brewery in Haarlem, is housed in a converted church on the outskirts of the city's medieval town center. The brewery offers a unique experience with its luxurious cafe, taproom, and museum where visitors can sample their delicious brews straight from the barrel. This former church has been transformed into a beer temple that attracts both locals and tourists alike.
name: Jopen

excerpt: 18th-century riverside windmill with scenic views, an educational museum & guided tours.
detail_description: Windmill De Adriaan (1779) is an 18th-century windmill turned museum located along the picturesque Spaarne River in Haarlem, Netherlands. It offers guided tours and a chance to explore its inner workings while enjoying stunning views of the river and surrounding countryside. Originally built on the northern support of the city's defenses, it has since become a symbol of Dutch history and the role windmills played in daily life.
name: Windmill De Adriaan (1779)

excerpt: Haarlem is a city outside of Amsterdam in the northwest Netherlands. Once a major North Sea trading port surrounded by a defensive wall, it retains its medieval character of cobblestone streets and gabled houses. It's the center of a major flower-bulb-growing district, and famous for its outlying tulip fields, art museums and hofjes (almshouses built around leafy courtyards).
detail_description: Haarlem, located just outside of Amsterdam in the northwest Netherlands, is a city with a rich history. Once a prominent North Sea trading port enclosed by defensive walls, it has preserved its medieval charm with cobblestone streets and traditional gabled houses. The area is renowned for its vibrant flower-bulb-growing district and picturesque tulip fields. Haarlem also boasts art museums and hofjes, which are almshouses built around serene courtyards.
name: Haarlem

excerpt: Many notable buildings & cafes surround this central plaza with a twice-weekly farmers’ market.
detail_description: Grote Markt is a bustling central plaza surrounded by impressive buildings and charming cafes. It is also home to a vibrant farmers' market that takes place twice a week. The square is not only a hub for local commerce but also an inviting space to relax and enjoy the surroundings. Visitors can immerse themselves in the lively atmosphere, grab a drink at one of the nearby cafes, and take in the historic charm of this iconic location.
name: Grote Markt

detail_description: Haarlem, a medieval city in the Netherlands, is surrounded by charming canals and characterized by its picturesque streets, monuments, and the stunning Grote Markt square. The city offers unique shops to explore and is rich in art and culture with renowned museums like Teylers Museum and De Hallen. With its ancient buildings, cobblestone streets, and waterways, Haarlem is a photogenic destination easily accessible from Amsterdam.
name: Haarlem

excerpt: National park with beaches, sand-dunes, wild deer & ponies, plus biking, hiking & horseback riding.
detail_description: Zuid-Kennemerland National Park is a serene natural escape located just 5 kilometers west of Haarlem. Spanning 3800 hectares, the park features beaches, sand dunes, forests, grasslands, and small lakes. It serves as an important defense against the sea and is home to native vegetation and designated nature reserves.
name: Nationaal Park Zuid-Kennemerland

excerpt: Catholic basilica, built 1895–1930 & dedicated in 1948, named for the city's patron saint.
detail_description: The Saint Bavo of Ghent Catholic Cathedral, Leidsevaart is a magnificent basilica located just outside the city center of Haarlem in the Netherlands. It was built from 1895 to 1930 and dedicated in 1948, named after the city's patron saint. The cathedral showcases eclectic and neo-renaissance architecture that leaves visitors in awe.
name: Saint Bavo of Ghent Catholic Cathedral, Leidsevaart

detail_description: Located along the beautiful Spaarne River just outside the historic center, there's a delightful brunch spot with an amazing interior, cozy atmosphere, and a sunny waterside terrace offering perfect views of passing boats. In addition to dine-in options, they also provide delicious takeout and delivery through their partners. Haarlem is often overlooked in favor of Amsterdam, but its tranquility and spaciousness make it equally enjoyable.
name: Spaarne

detail_description: When visiting Haarlem, be sure to explore the impressive City Hall and the grand Stg. Restauratiefonds Grote- of Sint Bavo Kerk te Haarlem, also known as St. Bavokerk. It's worth noting that Mozart had the opportunity to showcase his talent on the church's remarkable 5000-pipe Muller organ during his childhood.
name: Stg. Restauratiefonds Grote- of Sint Bavo Kerk te Haarlem

detail_description: St.-Bavokerk, also known as St. Bavo Cathedral, is a Gothic church located in the central market square of Haarlem. Its 262-foot-high tower dominates the city's skyline and has notable choir screens and stalls, Frans Hals' tomb, and a famous pipe organ made by Christian Muller in 1738. The church has undergone exterior renovations over the years while preserving its interior. Visitors can enjoy the picturesque view of St.
name: St.-Bavokerk

excerpt: The seat of the city's government, dating from the 14th c., with a collection of historical artwork.
detail_description: Town Hall Haarlem, dating back to the 14th century, serves as the city's government seat and houses a collection of historical artwork. The town offers a tour covering various beloved sites such as Grote Kerk of Sint Bavo, Grote Markt historic town market square, Molen Adriaan Windmill, Teylers Museum, and an enchanting Hofje with its secret walled garden.
name: Town Hall Haarlem

detail_description: Hofje Zonder Zorgen is a charming courtyard located in the heart of Haarlem, adjacent to the Proveniershofje. The courtyard is a must-visit landmark and offers a tranquil escape with its secret walled garden.
name: Hofje Zonder Zorgen

detail_description: By Lima is a cozy coffee shop located in central Haarlem, Netherlands. It offers a variety of organic food options made with local ingredients and features an all-day breakfast menu. The spot is known for its vibrant flavors of vegan cuisine, making it a go-to place for healthy breakfasts and brunches.
name: by LIMA

excerpt: Historic treed space featuring a petting farm, tea house, music chapel, deer park & pancake eatery.
detail_description: Theehuis de Haarlemmerhout is a historic and picturesque destination in Haarlem, known for its blend of art, nature, and culinary delights. As the oldest public park in the Netherlands, it has retained its original design from the 1500s with sprawling woodlands and scenic trails. The park features various monuments and sculptures that pay homage to historical figures like Laurens Janszoon Coster.
name: Theehuis de Haarlemmerhout

detail_description: DeDAKKAS is a unique spot in Haarlem, located on the roof of a parking garage in the city center. It's an actual greenhouse where visitors can enjoy lunch, drinks, and dinner with a fantastic view. The food is of high quality, featuring locally sourced or impact-driven ingredients. The menu changes seasonally to showcase products available in the Netherlands during that time, focusing mainly on plant-based items while also offering meat and fish options.
name: DeDAKKAS
address: on the roof, De Witstraat 1A, 2011 DV Haarlem, Netherlands

excerpt: Art-rich towering Gothic church, home to the ornate Muller organ, played by both Handel & Mozart.
detail_description: The St. Bavo Church in Haarlem is a magnificent Gothic church located in the heart of the city. It features a towering 50m-high steeple and houses the famous Muller organ, which dates back to 1738 and boasts around 5000 pipes. This ornate church has been graced by performances from renowned musicians such as Handel and Mozart, who played the impressive organ at a young age.
name: The St. Bavo Church in Haarlem

excerpt: 16th-century hospital building, now housing a museum of local history with a model city.
detail_description: Museum Haarlem is housed in a 16th-century hospital building and offers a glimpse into the history of the city. It features exhibits on local crafts, industries, and everyday life throughout the centuries. The museum also includes a model city and showcases the history of Haarlem from 1000 years ago to the present day.
name: Verwey Museum Haarlem

detail_description: Native Haarlem - Koffie, established in early 2016, is a popular spot in the heart of Haarlem for coffee enthusiasts. The cafe offers top-notch coffee from White Label Coffee, a specialty roaster from Amsterdam. In addition to their renowned coffee, Native also serves delectable organic and often gluten-free sandwiches and pastries. The cozy interior adorned with greenery and vintage decor creates a welcoming ambiance for patrons to linger over their drinks and food.
name: Native Haarlem - Koffie

detail_description: Grote Markt is the vibrant center of Haarlem, where the city's bustling streets converge. It's a hub of activity, hosting the lively Saturday market and exciting events like Kings Fair and Haarlem Culinary Festival. This square serves as an ideal starting point for exploring Haarlem on foot, making it a must-visit for any traveler looking to immerse themselves in the local culture.
name: Grote Markt

excerpt: Museum with guided tours of a onetime family home used to hide Jews during World War II.
detail_description: The Ten Boom Museum in Haarlem is a significant historical site dedicated to the memory of Corrie ten Boom, who bravely sheltered Jews and resistance fighters during World War II. The museum offers guided tours throughout the day, allowing visitors to explore the onetime family home and learn about its role in providing a hiding place for persecuted individuals. Similar to the Anne Frank House, this museum provides insight into the dark days of the Holocaust but without long waiting lines.
name: Ten Boom Museum

excerpt: Ruins of a 13th-century brick castle built by William I van Brederode & surrounded by a moat.
detail_description: The ruins of a 13th-century brick castle built by William I van Brederode & surrounded by a moat is found in this town near the city of Haarlem. It is a beautiful and peaceful place, very child friendly, and everyone who was working at the Castel was extremely friendly. Really enjoyed time.
name: Brederode Castle

excerpt: Originally an almshouse, these historical brick residences surround a scenic courtyard.
detail_description: The Proveniershuis is a historical complex of brick residences that originally served as an almshouse. Located just a short walk from the Grote Markt, this hofje was built in the 1500s and has undergone various transformations over the years, including housing elderly men and serving as a nunnery.
name: Proveniershuis

detail_description: Nieuwe Kerk, a Protestant church in Haarlem, is a historic building dating back to the early 1600s. It features a striking bell tower with an ornate dome and gilded clock face, standing out with its unique classical design. The church is renowned for its Baroque tomb of William of Orange, crafted by the talented artists Hendrick and Pieter de Keyser. Its Renaissance tower and clock from 1795 add to the charm of this ancient structure.
name: Nieuwe Kerk

detail_description: Jetties is a health food restaurant located in Haarlem, Netherlands, offering a variety of organic and homemade dishes such as burgers, pastas, soups, and daily specials. The menu features an array of options including 100% organic meat burgers and a veggie burger. In addition to their delicious fare, Jetties also serves fairtrade coffee and tea with vegan desserts. The cozy atmosphere adds to the dining experience where everything is prepared with love using responsibly sourced ingredients.
name: Jetties

detail_description: City Hall is a prominent civic building that serves as the administrative center of a municipality. It is a symbol of local governance and houses various governmental offices responsible for public services and decision-making. This municipal building, also known as town hall or council house, plays a crucial role in the governance of the city. It functions as a hub for important meetings, policy discussions, and collaboration among elected officials, bureaucrats, and citizens.
name: City Hall

detail_description: FrietHoes has left a positive impression on visitors, with one expressing consideration of including the product in their range after being impressed by the trial package. The establishment is praised for baking the tastiest fries in the Netherlands and is described as a super nice fries factory. It's known for offering deliciously baked fries, making it a must-visit spot for those craving quality potato treats.
name: FrietHoes

detail_description: Located on a pedestrian zone in the city of Haarlem, the Laurens Janszoon Coster Monument is a bronze statue installed in 1856. Positioned on a pedestal, this monument stands as a tribute to Laurens Coster and his alleged claim alongside Gutenberg to the invention of printing with movable type. It is situated north of the Grote Kerk and holds historical significance for the locals.
name: Laurens Janszoon Coster Monument

detail_description: Bakenes is a charming neighborhood located on an island, accessible via the Catharijnebrug bridge. The area is known for its historic houses and hofjes, with notable attractions such as the Bakenessekerk, a 15th-century church featuring an intricate white tower. Visitors can also explore Teylers Hofje, a peaceful courtyard and garden offering a serene retreat within this picturesque district.
name: Bakenes

detail_description: Market Square Consult is located at the charming Grote Markt, a historic town square where 10 streets meet. This iconic centerpiece has been a hub of activity for over 700 years, offering visitors a quintessential European experience. Here, one can savor the Dutch way of life by enjoying a coffee or beer while soaking in the delightful atmosphere.
name: Market Square Consult

excerpt: Art museum in a historic space with a focus on modern & contemporary works, photography & video art.
detail_description: De Hallen Haarlem is a captivating art museum located in a historic space, offering a focus on modern and contemporary works, photography, and video art. The museum boasts an impressive collection that includes the 17th-century Haarlem School with exceptional attention to mood and psychological tone. Additionally, it features works by renowned artists such as Pieter Bruegel the Younger and Jacob van Ruisdael.
name: De Hallen Haarlem

excerpt: Catholic basilica, built 1895–1930 & dedicated in 1948, named for the city's patron saint.
detail_description: The Cathedral of St. Bavo is a relatively recent three-aisle cruciform basilica built between 1895 and 1906. The church is notable for its beautiful treasury with valuable silver liturgical utensils as well as the reliquary containing the remains of Saint Bavo.
name: Saint Bavo of Ghent Catholic Cathedral, Leidsevaart

excerpt: Interactive exhibits on psychiatry in a 16th-century former mental institution & leper home.
detail_description: Het Dolhuys, located in a 16th-century former mental institution and leper home, has been transformed into a captivating museum that delves into the lives of individuals on the fringes of society. The museum aims to challenge perceptions about mental illness by showcasing the works of artists, writers, and scientists who dealt with disabilities or mental health issues. Through interactive exhibits, Het Dolhuys seeks to dispel myths surrounding mental illness and foster new attitudes towards psychiatry.
name: Het Dolhuys

detail_description: Amsterdamse Poort in Haarlem is a picturesque and historic corner, surrounded by some of the city's oldest and most stunning buildings. It served as a protection fortification for Haarlem during the 17th century and has undergone extensive renovation to restore its former glory. This 14th-century gate was part of the city wall and is the only one that survived over the centuries.
name: Amsterdamse Poort, Haarlem

excerpt: Small museum in lower level of 17th-c. Vleeshal building presenting local archaeology exhibits.
detail_description: Archeological Museum Haarlem is a small yet captivating museum situated in the cellar of the historic Vleeshal building, dating back to the 17th century. The museum offers an intriguing display of local archaeological findings, some dating as far back as 6,000 years ago. Visitors can engage in interactive activities such as mock excavations and artifact puzzles, making it an ideal destination for families with children.
name: Archeological Museum Haarlem

detail_description: Hofje van Bakenes is a beautiful and historic almshouse courtyard located in Haarlem, the Netherlands. Dating back to 1395, it is considered one of the oldest hofjes in the country. The well-maintained seventeenth-century houses and peaceful garden make it a hidden gem worth visiting. Despite being rebuilt in the 18th century, its historical significance remains intact.
name: Hofje van Bakenes

detail_description: De Vishal, which translates to "fish hall," is a contemporary and modern visual arts and design exhibition space located in Haarlem. Originally a fish market for saltwater fish, it now showcases art from local and international artists. With new exhibitions every five weeks, visitors can enjoy a diverse range of art for free. The gallery is run by passionate volunteers and often features hidden gems in temporary exhibitions. One notable exhibition worth mentioning is Lantic Scapes.
name: De Vishal

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Haarlem, Haarlemmer Kweektuin is a delightful green sanctuary that seamlessly combines nature with sustainability. Spanning an impressive 4.2 hectares, this park attracts around 50,000 visitors each year while still offering ample space to unwind and explore its lush surroundings. The organic garden and greenhouse are perfect for those interested in eco-friendly practices, while the Kweekcafe serves up delicious local dishes and homemade treats in a cozy atmosphere adorned with recycled furniture.
name: Haarlemmer Kweektuin

excerpt: Small, urban zoo providing a variety of animals, including mammals, birds, amphibians & more.
detail_description: Nestled in the charming city of Haarlem, Artisklas Haarlem stands out as the smallest official zoo in the Netherlands, offering a delightful escape into nature right within an urban setting. This cozy little zoo is entirely operated by dedicated volunteers who are passionate about sharing their love for animals with visitors. Open only on weekends, it features a diverse array of creatures including mammals, birds, and amphibians that will surely captivate both young and old alike.
name: Artisklas Haarlem
address: Arthur van Schendelpad 1, 2024 CP Haarlem, Netherlands

detail_description: St. Janskerk, an Order of Knights of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem cloister, constructed in 1318, is the oldest preserved church in the Netherlands and a remarkable representation of a repurposed Middle Ages cloister chapel. It currently serves as the Noord-Hollands Archief, while maintaining its original state. This historical site offers visitors a wonderful experience with its charming ambiance and hospitable staff.
name: Voormalige Janskerk

detail_description: Teylers Hofje is a charming and peaceful courtyard located on the banks of the Spaarne, near Gouden Straatjes in the centrum. It features a beautiful old building with a grand entrance off the canal, creating a serene atmosphere for visitors. The hofje is often included in sightseeing tours and offers a lovely indoor garden to explore.
name: Teylers Hofje

detail_description: Kenaupark, a charming 19th-century oasis nestled in the heart of Haarlem, is named after the courageous Kenau Simonsdochter Hasselaer, who valiantly defended the city during the siege of 1573. This delightful park features lush lawns, vibrant flower beds, and towering trees that create an inviting atmosphere for leisurely strolls or moments of peaceful reflection.
name: Kenaupark

detail_description: Nestled along the Kruisstraat, Hofje van Oorschot is a charming historical site that dates back to 1769. Established through the legacy of Amsterdam merchant Wouter van Oorschot, this lovely courtyard was designed to provide shelter for impoverished women aged 50 and above who were part of the Reformed church.
name: Hofje van Oorschot

detail_description: Gasthuis-Huisjes, a renowned historical landmark, stands as an emblem of the past. This distinguished architectural gem encapsulates a rich historical narrative that spans centuries. The Gasthuis-Huisjes structure represents a bygone era and showcases remarkable craftsmanship from yesteryear. With its impressive design and unique character, this celebrated heritage site embodies the spirit of cultural preservation and serves as a testament to the enduring legacy of our ancestors.
name: Gasthuis-Huisjes

detail_description: The Hofje van Staats is a historical landmark that boasts an interesting and significant background. This monument, situated in the heart of the city, holds immense cultural value. The Hofje van Staats is renowned for its rich heritage and architectural brilliance. It serves as a testament to the past and offers an intriguing glimpse into bygone eras. This site has garnered attention from locals and tourists alike due to its captivating history and remarkable design.
name: Hofje van Staats

detail_description: The Monument of Folk Hero Kenau Simonsdochter Hasselaer and Legendary City Governor Wigbolt (Baron) Ripperda is a large bronze statue depicting two historical figures who played crucial roles during the Siege of Haarlem in 1572-1573. Kenau was known for her fearlessness, while Governor Wigbolt inspired citizens to defend the city. The statue stands in a newly designed square in front of Haarlem central station, adding historical significance to the area.
name: Monument Of Folk Hero Kenau Simonsdochter Hasselaer And Legendary City Governor Wigbolt (Baron) Ripperda

detail_description: Municipal Theater Haarlem, located in a former church, offers a unique experience with its large stained-glass windows and soaring ceilings. Visitors can enjoy a variety of performances in this beautiful and spacious venue, with every seat offering a good view of the stage. The theater's intimate setting adds to the overall experience, making it an ideal place for an enjoyable evening out.
name: Municipal Theater Haarlem

detail_description: The Statue of Laurens Jansz Coster stands prominently on the main market square, honoring the 15th-century Haarlem figure traditionally credited with inventing the printing press in 1423. However, there is now uncertainty about his role as the inventor, with many historians attributing this achievement to Johannes Gutenberg from Germany in 1452. The statue itself was crafted in 1722 and remains a significant historical landmark in Haarlem.
name: Statue of Laurens Jansz Coster
